DISTRIBUTION

How a wireguard-go-bridge version reaches consumers — from a local
version bump to a public download from R2.


Pipeline overview
-----------------

  1. Bump        Local script updates both version sources and creates
                 a single commit on dev/wireguard-go-bridge.
  2. Push        Push the bump commit. Two CI workflows fire
                 automatically: test and build. They produce artifacts
                 but do not publish.
  3. Verify      Operator inspects the test + build artifacts on the
                 GitHub Actions run page. No release happens until the
                 operator is satisfied.
  4. Publish     Operator runs publish.sh, which dispatches the publish
                 workflow with no arguments.
  5. R2 upload   Publish workflow re-runs test + build, validates that
                 the Python and Go version sources agree, then uploads
                 to R2 under both versioned and latest paths.
  6. Consumption Downstream consumers fetch a per-arch zip from
                 vendor.phantom.tc over HTTPS.


Stage 1 — Bump
--------------

  .github/scripts/bump.sh [major|minor|patch]

  Defaults to patch. Updates both version sources atomically:

      wireguard_go_bridge/__init__.py  →  __version__
      src/version.go                   →  BridgeVersionStr

  Refuses to run if the two are already out of sync (the publish
  workflow rejects mismatches anyway; this catches it locally).
  Verifies the post-write values, then creates a single commit:

      Bump v<NEW_VERSION>

  Only the two version files are staged.


Stage 2 — Push
--------------

  git push origin dev/wireguard-go-bridge

  Two workflows fire on the bump commit (and on every push to this
  branch that touches non-.github paths):

      test-wireguard-go-bridge.yml    pytest inside Docker, 3-container
                                      topology (bridge + exit-server +
                                      client). 51 unit + 1 integration
                                      test. Artifact: test-results (30d).

      build-wireguard-go-bridge.yml   cgo cross-compile for linux-amd64
                                      and linux-arm64. Artifacts:
                                      wireguard-go-bridge-linux-amd64
                                      and -arm64 (90d).

  Neither workflow uploads to R2. They exist to give the operator a
  pass/fail signal and downloadable artifacts for inspection.


Stage 3 — Verify
----------------

  The operator opens the GitHub Actions run page and confirms both
  workflows are green. If anything is wrong, follow-up commits land
  on top of the bump commit. The bump itself is rarely amended —
  the version stays the same and the fixes ride on top.


Stage 4 — Publish trigger
-------------------------

  .github/scripts/publish.sh

  No arguments. Reads the version from
  wireguard_go_bridge/__init__.py and dispatches
  publish-wireguard-go-bridge.yml on the dev/wireguard-go-bridge ref
  via the GitHub CLI (gh workflow run).


Stage 5 — Publish workflow
--------------------------

  publish-wireguard-go-bridge.yml runs four jobs in sequence:

      version    Extracts the version from __init__.py.
                 Validates that src/version.go matches.
                 Aborts the entire run on mismatch.

      test       Re-runs the full test suite via workflow_call.
                 Treated as a release gate — failure stops the publish.

      build      Re-runs the linux-amd64 and linux-arm64 builds via
                 workflow_call.

      publish    Self-hosted runner with rclone configured against the
                 R2 remote. Packages each architecture into a zip,
                 verifies sha256 checksums, uploads to R2 under both
                 v<VERSION>/ and latest/ paths.


Stage 6 — R2 storage
--------------------

  Bucket : phantom-vendor
  Domain : vendor.phantom.tc

  Each publish writes to two locations simultaneously:

      wireguard-go-bridge/v<VERSION>/      pinned, immutable
      wireguard-go-bridge/latest/          moves on every publish

  Both contain the same three files:

      linux-amd64.zip     Python package + .so for linux/amd64
      linux-arm64.zip     Python package + .so for linux/arm64
      VERSION             plain-text version string at the path level

  Each zip contains a single top-level wireguard_go_bridge/ directory:

      wireguard_go_bridge/
        __init__.py
        _ffi.py
        bridge.py
        keys.py
        types.py
        wireguard_go_bridge.so
        wireguard_go_bridge.so.sha256
        VERSION

  The VERSION file is duplicated (path-level + inside the zip) so
  consumers can tell which version they have without unzipping.


Stage 7 — Consumption
---------------------

  Consumers download over HTTPS. Two strategies:

      Pinned to a known version (recommended):
        https://vendor.phantom.tc/wireguard-go-bridge/v<VERSION>/linux-amd64.zip

      Tracking the moving latest pointer:
        https://vendor.phantom.tc/wireguard-go-bridge/latest/linux-amd64.zip

  After extraction, the runtime version can be confirmed two ways:

      cat wireguard_go_bridge/VERSION
      python -c "from wireguard_go_bridge import __version__; print(__version__)"

  Both should agree with the URL the artifact came from. If they
  disagree, the deployed copy was tampered with or the build pipeline
  has a bug — either way, do not use it.


End-to-end example
------------------

  $ .github/scripts/bump.sh patch
  2.1.2 → 2.1.3
  [dev/wireguard-go-bridge abcdef0] Bump v2.1.3

  $ git push origin dev/wireguard-go-bridge
  ...
  # → test + build workflows fire on GitHub Actions, ~5-10 min each.

  # Operator opens the run page, confirms green check on both runs.

  $ .github/scripts/publish.sh
  Version : v2.1.3
  Workflow: publish-wireguard-go-bridge.yml
  Ref     : dev/wireguard-go-bridge
  Triggered. Watch: gh run list --repo ARAS-Workspace/phantom-wg --workflow publish-wireguard-go-bridge.yml

  # → publish workflow runs version → test → build → publish,
  #   ~15-25 min total. R2 receives the new artifacts.

  # Consumers can now fetch:
  #   https://vendor.phantom.tc/wireguard-go-bridge/v2.1.3/linux-amd64.zip
  #   https://vendor.phantom.tc/wireguard-go-bridge/latest/linux-amd64.zip


Rollback
--------

  No artifacts are deleted from R2. If a bad version goes out:

  1. Bump again (patch) and publish a new fixed version. The latest/
     path moves forward to the new build immediately.

  2. Pinned consumers stay on the bad version until they update
     their pin. Communicate the issue out-of-band.

  3. Optionally rewrite latest/ manually to point at the previous
     known-good v<VERSION>/ contents using rclone — but this leaves
     the bad bits at v<VERSION>/, so prefer step 1.


Notes
-----

  * Changes under .github/ do not trigger test/build on push
    (paths-ignore on the workflows).

  * The test workflow runs the same Docker topology used in local
    development (test_runner.py) — no environment drift between
    local and CI.

  * Publish runs on a self-hosted runner because the R2 credentials
    live there, not in GitHub Secrets.

  * The standalone VERSION file at the R2 path level lets consumers
    do a HEAD-style check ("what version is at latest/ right now?")
    without downloading a multi-megabyte zip.
